          "title": "The remnant — the holy seed is its stump",
          "body": "Isaiah's 'how long?' (6:11) is met not with comfort but with the duration of devastation. Cities will be without inhabitant; houses without people; the land utterly desolate. The Lord will remove men far away (the exile, foretold a century and a half before Babylon takes Jerusalem in 586 BC). And then — the chapter's final word — *yet*. A tenth remains; subjected again to burning; like a felled terebinth or oak whose stump remains. 'The holy seed is its stump' (6:13). The vocabulary of *qodesh* returns from 6:3 — the Lord whose holiness undid Isaiah is the Lord whose holiness preserves a seed. Christologically read, this stump is the remnant from which the Branch of 11:1 will shoot — the messianic Branch from Jesse's stock. John 12:41 confirms what Isaiah's chapter implies: the Lord enthroned in 6:1 is the Christ who will be lifted up. The holy seed Israel could not produce, the Lord Himself becomes."
